xxx
xx
Jxx
KQxxx

AK
AK
AT987x
ATx

(We bid 2C-2D; 2NT-3NT, but even had I opened 1D, I doubt we get to
6D.  Only a strong club with relays gets to 6D, I fear).

So here is my question.

What is mathematically the safest list for limiting diamond losers to
1?

Playing the AD and a diamond wins on all 2-2 breaks (40%) plus half of
the 3-1 breaks (additional 25%) for a total of 65%.

Playing for clubs 3-2 (68%) and taking two finesses wins against all
2-2 (40%) and 3-1 (50%) breaks unless the KQ diamonds is doubleton
offside (16.7% of the 40% chance = 6.67%).

So my calculations suggest that playing the AD and a diamond will win
about 65% of the time but the two finesess line will win about 56% of
the time (83% of 68%).

Not being a mathmetician, can anyone verify that these numbers are
ballpark correct?

Thanks,

Henrysun909
