What source are you citing from which requires 1.5 QT for a positive
response in Standard American?
I have have never heard of this requirement.

If you are playing 2D waiting which is a fairly common choice in the
US, you could have more than 1.5 QT for a 2D response. For example,
partner could have S Axx   H AKx   D xxx   C xxxx and this hand has 3
QT. In Max Hardy's book in two over one (which is essentially Walsh),
&quot;With a five card or longer suit which includes two of the top three
honors cards, responder to 2C bids his suit at the cheapest level.&quot;

The logic for this is if you have controls you can always find out
them later and if responder has a better hand he knows when to keep
the bidding alive. But if you have a hand with a source of tricks it
is nearly impossible to tell partner this after showing controls.
Also, if you don't bid a suit right away but bid the suit later
partner knows you need a lot more help in the suit.

After bidding 3C with this hand, little can go wrong. If partner
intended to rebid 2NT he will rebid 3NT and you will be happy to pass
as you would have raised to 3NT anyway. If partner bids a suit you
know partner has promised a trick under game and you have that trick
so the auction is forcing to game. The big advantage to showing a
source of tricks happens when you get a pair of hands like the example
here and you can't show the club suit.

