Eric makes the interesting point that perhaps my brother should have
responded 3C = good suit instead of making a negative/neutral 2D
response.  Surely this would have been more attractive had his clubs
been a major.  We don't play the style were positive = good suit, 2D =
denies good suit although I know if it from the days of Western Roth-
Stone (and when I picked up Aces Scientific much later in life).

Still, Goldman concedes - correctly - that specifically the 3C
response should be looser with respect to suit quality because of the
artificial second negative (2C-2D; 2MN-3C) which prevernt a hand like

x
Axx
xxx
KJxxxx

from bidding 3C naturally.

The idea proposed by Travis, that 3NT would be forcing after a
positive response, has its roots in the idea that a strong two +
positive response = slam.  When a positive shows a good suit, that
arithmetic no longer holds.  Give response a slightly stronger hand
(so that the issue of whether the hand is a positive response is moot)
and opener a strong/misfitting hand and you'll see what 3NT should not
be played as forcing, e.g.:

Kx
xxx
xxx
KQxxx

AQxx
AKJx
AKQ
xx

Now you pretty much need clubs 3-3 with the ace onside to have play
for slam, and that's about a 20% slam.  (I could have cooked the hand
by giving opener 4=4=4=1 shape, of course.)

The issue of what game bids are forcing after a positive response is
one that hasn't really been explored.  There was a hand in the MSC
some years ago when opener held something on the order of:

AKJxxxx
AKQxx
VOID
x

After opening 2C (even the most ardent supporters of 'don't bid 2C
with a two suiter should have no problems with opening this hand with
2C) and hearing the auction go:

2C     3D (natural/positive)
3S     3NT
?

Much ink was used on the question of whether 4H by opener would be
forcing.  Those who bid 4H generally felt it was forcing and some who
rebid 4S did so because they feared 4H was forcing.  After all, give
responder a hand like

x
xx
KQTxxx
KJxx

and so you really want to play anywhere besideds 4S?  And if opener
did rebid 4H, would this be the sort of hand on which one would give
false preference to 4S?

So while Eric is right on the initial sequence (2C-3C; 3NT should not
be played as forcing), the more general question of what game bids ARE
forcing in 2C sequences is, to me, a still unresolved question.

