In the case of KQx or KQ it doesn't matter whether it is covered
or not, because declarer can't play it wrong.

Defender doesn't know if declarer has 6 or 7 diamonds.

So partner could have singleton K or Q and covering
with Kx or Qx when partner has the other singleton honor
gives up the whole suit. Your lead the Jack and see if they
hesitate might work against Intermediate players and below
but certainly not good players, so it is best to select the
mathematically superior approach which is to play for the drop.

AKxxx

Qxx             J

T9xx

or

AKxxx

QJx             x

T9xx

or

AKxxx

QJx

T9xxx

In all these cases defenders know not to cover the Ten because
they know declarer is governed by 8 never, nine never dictum.
Hoping your opps are bad players and misdefend is a less than
optimum approach to selecting a winning line of play. It made
me wonder, who does this guy play against? Against 4-4 fits, it
(not found in a unilateral 2C opener bidding his strong suit)
matters if you see the 8 in dummy, or dummy is short of entries.
