An old grand master bridge player once told me &quot;Every player has the
God given right to make a mistake.&quot;
So if you never give your opponents a chance to make a mistake it
stands to reason you can't get lucky.
You can go through your bridge life as a technician playing opponents
as abstract objects striving to find the last decimal point advantage
or you can try to be an artist. Being a technician is like comparing a
house painter to a Picasso..

I refer you to a hand I played which was reported at the Daily
Bulletin for the ACBL Nationals in Pittsburg in 2005 which was a
similar trump situation.

http://web2.acbl.org/nabcbulletins/2005spring/db10.pdf

see page 2.

I would submit a big part of the game is seizing upon nearly free
opportunities to induce error.

Eric Leong
